   </sec>
   <sec>
    <title>
     DC mutations and Shq1 binding
    </title>
    <p>
     A majority of X-linked DC mutations are clustered on the N- and C-terminal regions of Cbf5, part of which constitute the PUA domain (
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Marrone et al, 2005
     </xref>
     ). Compared with their archaeal counterparts, eukaryotic Cbf5 proteins contain the N-terminal extension (NTE) and CTE (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 6A
     </xref>
     ). These two extensions are highly conserved in eukaryotes and harbour many DC mutations. The crystal structure of the CNG complex showed that the NTE folds into a new structural layer covering on the PUA domain, whereas the CTE is disordered (
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Li et al, 2011
     </xref>
     ). The Shq1 complex structure now reveals a novel function for the CTE in mediating Shq1 association.
    </p>
    <fig id="f6" position="float">
     <label>
      Figure 6
     </label>     <caption>
      <p>
       DC mutations and Shq1 interaction. (
       <strong>
        A
       </strong>
       ) Sequence alignment around the Cbf5 PUA domain. The aligned Cbf5 sequences are from
       <em>
